[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Can 
[normal]the G
[normal]overnment confirm that it intends to apply the ‘indexed deduction’ method to adjusting the block grant for the 
[normal]introduction of devolved income
[normal]? 
[normal] What information can it supply about the impact of applying that reduction to the Welsh block grant?  
[normal]If an element of income tax is devolved following a referendum, the Government intends to apply the ‘indexed deduction’ mechanism to adjust the Welsh Government block grant as recommended by the Silk Commission (and which is also being implemented in Scotland).  
[normal]In the first year of operating this mechanism (as well as in any preceding transitional years) an amount equivalent to the revenues generated by the Welsh rate of income tax (at 10p) will be deducted from the block grant.  If the Welsh Government sets a rate of 10p then its budget will be unchanged during these years (as the deduction will be the same as the revenues generated by the Welsh rate of income tax). Setting a Welsh rate of 11p or 9p will lead to a higher or lower budget respectively (as the deduction will still be based on the 10p forfeited by the UK Government).  
[normal]In year 2 onwards, the deduction from the previous year will be indexed against growth in the UK non savings non dividend (NSND) 
[normal]income tax base,
[normal]  
[normal]i
[normal].e. if the UK NSND income tax base grows by, for example, 1% or -5%, then so will the deduction. The Welsh Government budget will therefore benefit from these new arrangements when the NSND income tax base grows more quickly in Wales than the UK average (and conversely the budget will be lower if growth is slower).  
[normal]By linking the Welsh Government budget to the performance of the Welsh economy, this increases accountability and provides a further incentive to create growth.  But at the same time this mechanism shields the Welsh Government budget from UK-wide effects that the UK Government is better placed to manage (as the Welsh Government budget is only affected by the relative performance of the Welsh and UK NSND income tax base).
[normal]4. 
[normal]What approaches will be used to calculate 
[normal]reductions
[normal] from the block grant for stamp duty land tax and landfill tax?  
[normal]The UK and Scottish Governments are currently discussing the most appropriate block grant adjustment mechanism in relation to stamp duty land tax and landfill tax.  The Scotland Bill Command Paper indicated that this would be a one-off adjustment but the precise nature of that adjustment is still to be agreed.  
[normal]The UK Government has now opened similar discussions with the Welsh Government, with the intention that the same mechanism can be agreed for both Wales and Scotland.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The
[normal] definition of a Scottish taxpayer inserted by the
[normal] Scotland Act 2012 
[normal]sets out that,
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal]f an individual has a main place of residence for the same amount of time, or spends the same number of days, in Scotland as in another part of the 
[normal]UK;
[normal] they will be a Scottish taxpayer. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This means that the definition of a Welsh taxpayer cannot be identically drafted to the parallel provision in Scotland, as this would mean a taxpayer could be both a Welsh and Scottish taxpayer in the same year
[normal] if
[normal],
[normal] for example, their main place of residence was in each country for an equal amount of time.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Options to resolve thi
[normal]s issue are currently being considered
[normal] and will be included in the final Bill.
[normal] 
