[normal] Could you clarify paragraph 66 in the explanatory notes on reliefs. It seems there are discussions yet to be had between the Government and stakeholders on the devolution of reliefs. How will this process work? What powers will the Welsh Government have over reliefs under the proposals?
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]HMRC consulted representatives from private sector 
[normal]representative
[normal] group
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]on
[normal] the impact of the Scottish rate of income tax on aspects of the UK income tax system including income tax reliefs.  The consultation 
[normal]contributed to 
[normal]the approach to the treatment of reliefs for Scottish taxpayers in 
[normal]HMRC’s Technical Note, published 
[normal]in 
[normal]May 2012
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Before making any orders under this section, to amend 
[normal]the application of the Welsh rate of 
[normal]income tax
[normal] to tax reliefs
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK Government would consult relevant stakeholders. 
[normal]Our starting point would be the results of the previous consultation, so we would expect that 
[normal]the approach taken in these areas, including the treatment of tax relief for charitable donations and pension contributions would follow the proposals in the
[normal] 
[normal]Technical Note
[normal], 
[normal]subject to
[normal] any changes in the tax system or 
[normal]in the capability of IT systems in the interim.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The devolution of income tax reliefs is not within scope of this Bill. 
[normal]The Welsh Government’s power relates only to the rate of income tax – we would expect the Welsh Government to be involved in 
[normal]consultation
[normal] in relation to reliefs, but the final decision would rest with the UK Government because of the potential for wider impacts on the income tax system as a whole.
