[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The draft Bill does not contain provision for devolving business rates to Wales.  Indeed, the term ‘business rates’ does not feature in the draft Bill. However, in the explanatory notes attached to the draft Bill it says “The draft Bill also implements the [Silk] Commission’s recommendation to fully devolve business rates in Wales. The Welsh Government budget would then be directly affected by revenues from business rates in Wales, reflecting the performance of the Welsh economy, rather than being determined by spending funded by business rates in England through the Barnett formula.” (p68). 
[normal] Do the proposed changes to business rates require statutory change, and if so where is this to be found 
[normal]the draft Bill? Which clauses do this? Could you please give a detailed explanation. 
[normal]The summary impact assessment refers in error to the inclusion of business rates in the draft Bill. We apologise unreservedly for this error. 
[normal]Legislative competence over business rates is already devolved to the National Assembly for Wales by virtue of the “local government finance” subject in heading 12 (local government) of Schedule 7 to the GoWA 2006. No further devolution of legislative competence is needed to effect the Government’s commitment to “work with the Welsh Government to fully devolve non-domestic (business) rates”
[normal], and so no provision is made in the draft Bill in relation to business rates.
[normal]Changes are needed to the way in which business rates affect the Welsh Government’s budget in order to implement full devolution. At present, changes to the Welsh Government’s budget in relation to business rates are  determined through the Barnett formula, following changes in spending funded by business rates in England, and so revenues generated by Welsh business rates have no direct effect on the Welsh Government’s budget. 
[normal]Discussions are underway between HM Treasury and the Welsh Government so that changes in business rates revenues in Wales directly affect the funds available to the Welsh Government (as is already the case in Scotland and Northern Ireland). This will link growth in the Welsh Government’s budget more closely to the performance of the Welsh economy. 
[normal]The aim of both Governments is to implement these changes as soon as possible.
