[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Could you clarify whether clause 11 means that the Secretary of State has the power to prevent a referendum on income tax devolution even if there has been a vote in favour in both the National Assembly for Wales and the Houses of Parliament?
[normal]Under clause 11 of the draft Bill, the Secretary of State may refuse to lay a draft order following a “trigger” vote passed by two thirds of the Assembly, and must give notice and reasons for that refusal to the First Minister within 180 days of receiving notification from the Assembly. This process is based on the same procedure which led to the referendum in March 2011 which led to full law-making powers for the National Assembly for Wales. Once the Order has been approved by both Houses of Parliament and the Assembly, in practice the Secretary of State has no power to prevent the Order being made by Her Majesty.
[normal]9
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Welsh Government’s borrowing capacity will be increased if there is a ‘yes’ vote in a referendum on income tax devolution. In that event, what mechanism is there to decide how much the borrowing capacity should be increased by?
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Government has set out a principle linking capital borrowing powers to the level of Devolved Administrations’ independent revenue.  This would suggest that the Welsh Government’s capital borrowing limit would be increased if an element of income tax were to be devolved.  The precise increase would be a matter for a future government, but the limit could be increased to slightly more than £1bn using the borrowing/revenue ratios applied in Scotland.  The draft Wales Bill includes the power for the capital borrowing limit to be amended but not to a level below the initial £500m.  
