[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]PART 4[bold]&#xa0;[bold]ACTS OF THE ASSEMBLY[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]108 Legislative competence[bold]&#xa0;
[normal](1) Subject to the provisions of this Part, an Act of the Assembly may make any provision that could be made by an Act of Parliament.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](2) An Act of the Assembly is not law so far as any provision of the Act is outside the Assembly's legislative competence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](3) A provision of an Act of the Assembly is within the Assembly's legislative competence only if it falls within subsection (4) or (5).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](4) A provision of an Act of the Assembly falls within this subsection if–
[normal](a) it relates to one or more of the subjects listed under any of the headings in Part 1 of Schedule 7 and
[normal], subject to subsection (4A),[bold] does not fall within any of the exceptions specified in that Part of that Schedule (whether or not under that heading or any of those headings), and
[normal](b) it neither applies otherwise than in relation to 
[normal]Wales
[normal] nor confers, imposes, modifies or removes (or gives power to confer, impose, modify or remove) functions exercisable otherwise than in relation to 
[normal]Wales
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](4A) Provision relating to a devolved tax (which is listed under the heading “Taxation” in Part 1 of Schedule 7) is not outside the Assembly’s legislative competence by reason only of the fact that it falls within an exception specified under another heading in that Part of that Schedule.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal](5) A provision of an Act of the Assembly falls within this subsection if–
[normal](a) it provides for the enforcement of a provision (of that or any other Act of the Assembly) which falls within subsection (4) or a provision of an Assembly Measure or it is otherwise appropriate for making such a provision effective, or 
[normal](b) it is otherwise incidental to, or consequential on, such a provision.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](6) But a provision which falls within subsection (4) or (5) is outside the Assembly's legislative competence if–
[normal](a) it breaches any of the restrictions in Part 2 of Schedule 7, having regard to any exception in Part 3 of that Schedule from those restrictions,
[normal](b) it extends otherwise than only to 
[normal]England
[normal] and 
[normal]Wales
[normal], or 
[normal](c) it is incompatible with the Convention rights or with EU law.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](7) For the purposes of this section the question whether a provision of an Act of the Assembly relates to one or more of the subjects listed in Part 1 of Schedule 7 (or falls within any of the exceptions specified in that Part of that Schedule) is to be determined by reference to the purpose of the provision, having regard (among other things) to its effect in all the circumstances.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]111 Proceedings on Bills[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) The standing orders must include provision–
[normal](a) for general debate on a Bill with an opportunity for Assembly members to vote on its general principles,
[normal](b) for the consideration of, and an opportunity for Assembly members to vote on, the
[normal]details of a Bill, and (c) for a final stage at which a Bill can be passed or rejected.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](2) Subsection (1) does not prevent the standing orders making provision to enable the Assembly to expedite proceedings in relation to a particular Bill.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](3) The standing orders may make provision different from that required by subsection (1) for the procedure applicable to Bills of any of the following kinds–
[normal](a) Bills which restate the law,
[normal](b) Bills which repeal or revoke spent enactments, and
[normal](c) private Bills.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](4) The standing orders must include provision for securing that the Assembly may only pass a Bill containing provisions which would, if contained in a Bill for an Act of Parliament, require the consent of Her Majesty or the Duke of Cornwall if such consent has been signified in accordance with the standing orders.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](5) The standing orders must include provision for securing that the Assembly may only pass a Bill if the text of the Bill is in both English and Welsh, unless the circumstances are such as are specified by the standing orders as any in which the text need not be in both languages.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](6) The standing orders must provide for an opportunity for the reconsideration of a Bill after its passing if (and only if)–
[normal](a) the Supreme Court decides on a reference made in relation to the Bill under section 112 that the Bill or any provision of it would not be within the Assembly's legislative competence,
[normal](b) a reference made in relation to the Bill under section 112 is withdrawn following a
[normal]request for withdrawal of the reference under section 113(2)(b), or
[normal](c) an order is made in relation to the Bill under section 114.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](7) The standing orders must, in particular, ensure that any Bill amended on reconsideration is subject to a final stage at which it can be approved or rejected.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](8) References in subsections (4), (5) and (6) of this section and sections 107(2), 109(5)
[normal] and 116(3)
[normal], 116(3) and 116B(4)[bold] [bold]to the passing of a Bill are, in the case of a Bill which has been amended on reconsideration, to be read as references to its approval.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]PART 4A[bold]&#xa0;[bold]TAXATION[bold]&#xa0;[bold]CHAPTER 1[bold]&#xa0;[bold]INTRODUCTORY[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116A Overview of Part 4A[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) In this Part–[bold](a) Chapter 2 confers on the Assembly power to set a rate of income tax to be paid by Welsh taxpayers, and[bold](b) Chapters 3 and 4 specify the taxes about which the Assembly may make provision in the exercise of the power conferred by section 107(1).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) The power to make provision about a devolved tax is subject to the restrictions imposed by–[bold](a) subsection (3), and[bold](b) the other provisions of this Part.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](3) A devolved tax may not be imposed where to do so would be incompatible with any international obligations.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](4) In this Act “devolved tax” means a tax specified in this Part as a devolved tax.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116B Power to add new devolved taxes[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) Her Majesty may by Order in Council amend this Part so as to–[bold](a) specify, as an additional devolved tax, a tax of any description, or[bold](b) make any other modifications of the provisions relating to devolved taxes which She considers appropriate.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) An Order in Council under this section may make such modifications of–[bold](a) any enactment (including any enactment comprised in or made under this Act) or prerogative instrument, or[bold](b) any other instrument or document, as Her Majesty considers appropriate in connection with the provision made by the Order.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](3) No recommendation is to be made to Her Majesty in Council to make an Order in Council under this section unless a draft of the statutory instrument containing the Order has been laid before, and approved by a resolution of, each House of Parliament and the Assembly.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](4) The amendment of this Part by an Order in Council under this section does not affect–[bold](a) the validity of an Act of the Assembly passed before the amendment comes into force, or[bold](b) the previous or continuing operation of such an Act of the Assembly.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]CHAPTER 2[bold]&#xa0;[bold]INCOME TAX[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]116C Power to set Welsh rate for Welsh taxpayers[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) The[bold] Assembly may by resolution (a “Welsh rate resolution”[bold]) set the Welsh rate for the purpose of calculating the rates of income tax to be paid by Welsh taxpayers.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) Section 6(2B) of the Income Tax Act 2007 provides for the calculation of those rates.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](3) A Welsh rate resolution applies–[bold](a) for only one tax year, and[bold](b) for the whole of that year.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](4) A Welsh rate resolution may specify only one rate.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](5) The Welsh rate must be a whole number or half a whole number.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](6) A Welsh rate resolution–[bold](a) must specify the tax year for which it applies,[bold](b) must be made before the start of that tax year, and[bold](c) must not be made more than 12 months before the start of that year.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](7) If a Welsh rate resolution is cancelled before the start of the tax year for which it is to apply–[bold](a) the Income Tax Acts have effect for that year as if the resolution had never been passed, and[bold](b) the resolution may be replaced by another Welsh rate resolution.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](8) The standing orders must provide that only the First Minister or a Welsh Minister appointed under section 48 may move a motion for a Welsh rate resolution.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116D Welsh taxpayers[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) In any tax year, a Welsh taxpayer is an individual (T) who, for that year–[bold](a) is resident in the [bold]UK[bold] for income tax purposes (see Schedule 45 to the Finance Act 2013), and[bold](b) meets condition A, B or C.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) T meets condition A if T has a close connection with [bold]Wales[bold] (see section 116E).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](3) T meets condition B if[bold]–[bold](a) T does not have a close connection with [bold]England[bold], [bold]Scotland[bold] or [bold]Northern Ireland[bold] (see section 116E), and[bold](b) T spends more days of that year in [bold]Wales[bold] than in any other part of the [bold]UK[bold] (see section 116F).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](4) T meets condition C if, for the whole or any part of the year, T is–[bold](a) a member of Parliament for a constituency in [bold]Wales[bold],[bold](b) a member of the European Parliament for [bold]Wales[bold], or[bold](c) an Assembly member.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](5) In this Chapter “the [bold]UK[bold]”[bold] means the [bold]United Kingdom[bold].[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116E Close connection with [bold]Wales[bold] or another part of the [bold]UK[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) To find whether, for any year, T has a close connection with any part of the [bold]UK[bold] see–[bold](a) subsection (2) (where T has only one place of residence in the [bold]UK[bold]), or[bold](b) subsection (3) (where T has 2 or more places of residence in the [bold]UK[bold]).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) T has a close connection with a part of the [bold]UK[bold] if in that year–[bold](a) T has only one place of residence in the [bold]UK[bold],[bold](b) that place of residence is in that part of the [bold]UK[bold], and[bold](c) for at least part of the year, T lives at that place.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](3) T has a close connection with a part of the [bold]UK[bold] if in that year–[bold](a) T has 2 or more places of residence in the [bold]UK[bold],[bold](b) for at least part of the year, T’s main place of residence in the [bold]UK[bold] is in that part of the [bold]UK[bold],[bold](c) the times in the year when T’s main place of residence is in that part of the UK comprise (in aggregate) at least as much of the year as[bold] [bold]the times when T’s main place of residence is in any one other part of the UK, and[bold](d) for at least part of the year, T lives at a place of residence in that part of the [bold]UK[bold].[bold]&#xa0;
[normal](4) In this section “place” includes a place on board a vessel or other means of transport.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116F Days spent in [bold]Wales[bold] or another part of the [bold]UK[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) T spends more days of a year in [bold]Wales[bold] than in any other part of the [bold]UK[bold] if (and only if) –[bold](a) the number of days in the year on which T is in [bold]Wales[bold] at the end of the day equals or exceeds[bold](b) the number of days in the year on which T is in any other part of the [bold]UK[bold] at the end of the day.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) But T is not to be treated as being in the [bold]UK[bold] at the end of a day if–[bold](a) on that day T arrives in the [bold]UK[bold] as a passenger,[bold](b) T departs from the [bold]UK[bold] on the next day, and[bold](c) during the time between arrival and departure T does not engage in activities which are to a substantial extent unrelated to T’s passage through the [bold]UK[bold].[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116G Supplemental powers to modify enactments[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) The Treasury may by order provide that subsections (2A), (2B) and (2D) of section 6 of the Income Tax Act 2007 are to be disapplied, or that their effect is to be modified, in relation to any enactment.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) The Treasury may by order make such modifications of any enactment as they consider necessary or expedient in consequence of or in connection with–[bold](a) the power of the Assembly to set a rate under section 116C;[bold](b) the making of a Welsh rate resolution;[bold](c) an order under subsection (1).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](3) An order under subsection (2) may, in particular, provide that a Welsh rate resolution does not require any change in the amounts repayable or deductible under PAYE regulations between–[bold](a) the beginning of the tax year for which the resolution has effect, and[bold](b) such date (falling after the date of the resolution) as may be specified in the order.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](4) An order under this section may, to the extent that the Treasury consider it to be appropriate, take effect retrospectively from the beginning of the tax year in which the order is made.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](5) No order is to be made under this section unless a draft of the statutory instrument containing it has been laid before, and approved by a resolution of, the House of Commons.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](6) Subsection (5) does not apply to an order under subsection (2) which makes only such provision as is mentioned in subsection (3); a statutory instrument containing such an order is subject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of the House of Commons.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116H Reimbursement of expenses[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The Welsh Ministers may reimburse any Minister of the Crown or government department for administrative expenses incurred by virtue of this Chapter at any time after the passing of the [bold]Wales[bold] Act 2014 by the Minister or department.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116I Report by the Comptroller and Auditor General[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) The Comptroller and Auditor General must for each financial year prepare a report on the matters set out in subsection (2).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) Those matters are–[bold](a) [bold]the adequacy of any of HMRC’[bold]s rules and procedures put in place, in consequence of the Welsh rate provisions, for the purpose of ensuring the proper assessment and collection of income tax charged at rates determined under those provisions,[bold](b) whether the rules and procedures described in paragraph (a) are being complied with,[bold](c) the correctness of the sums brought to account by HMRC which relate to income tax which is attributable to a Welsh rate resolution, and[bold](d) the accuracy and fairness of the amounts which are reimbursed to HMRC under section 116H (having been identified by it as administrative expenses incurred as a result of the charging of income tax as mentioned in paragraph (a)).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](3) The “Welsh rate provisions” are–[bold](a) this Chapter, and[bold](b) the amendments made by section 9 of the [bold]Wales[bold] Act 2014.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](4) A report under this section may also include an assessment of the economy, efficiency and effectiveness with which HMRC has used its resources in carrying out relevant functions.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal](5) “Relevant functions” are functions of HMRC in the performance of which HMRC incurs administrative expenses which are reimbursed to HMRC under section 116H (having been identified by it as administrative expenses incurred as a result of the charging of income tax as mentioned in subsection (2)(a)).[bold]&#xa0;[bold](6) HMRC must give the Comptroller and Auditor General such information as the Comptroller and Auditor General may reasonably require for the purposes of preparing a report under this section.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](7) A report prepared under this section must be laid before the Assembly not later than 31 January of the financial year following that to which the report relates.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](8) In this section “HMRC” means Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]CHAPTER 3[bold]&#xa0;[bold]TAX ON TRANSACTIONS INVOLVING INTERESTS IN LAND[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116J Tax on transactions involving interests in land[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) A tax charged on any of the following transactions is a devolved tax–[bold](a) the acquisition of an estate, interest, right or power in or over land in [bold]Wales[bold];[bold](b) the acquisition of the benefit of an obligation, restriction or condition affecting the value of any such estate, interest, right or power.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) The tax may be chargeable–[bold](a) whether or not there is any instrument effecting the transaction,[bold](b) if there is such an instrument, regardless of where it is executed, and[bold](c) regardless of where any party to the transaction is or is resident.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116K Certain transactions not taxable[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) Tax may not be imposed under section 116J on so much of a transaction as relates to land below mean low water mark.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) The following persons are not to be liable to pay a tax imposed under section 116J–[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Government[bold]A Minister of the Crown[bold]The Welsh Ministers, the First Minister and the Counsel General [bold]The Scottish Ministers [bold]A [bold]Northern Ireland[bold] department[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Parliament etc[bold]The Corporate Officer of the House of Lords [bold]The Corporate Officer of the House of Commons [bold]The Assembly Commission [bold]The Scottish Parliamentary Corporate Body [bold]The [bold]Northern Ireland[bold] Assembly Commission.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]CHAPTER 4[bold]&#xa0;[bold]TAX ON DISPOSALS TO LANDFILL[bold]&#xa0;[bold]116L Tax on disposals to landfill[bold]&#xa0;[bold](1) A tax charged on disposals to landfill made in [bold]Wales[bold] is a devolved tax.[bold]&#xa0;[bold](2) A disposal is a disposal to landfill if–[bold](a) it is a disposal of material as waste, and[bold](b) it is made by way of landfill.[bold]&#xa0;
